    "text": "Fig. 3.7. The typical relation between expected net gain, G(c), and the amount of milk stocked, c. The example assumes that one unit of milk costs 6 = 1 and is sold for s = 1.50. The demand is normally distributed, with mean 100 and standard deviation 20. (The normal distribution is not strictly positive, but for the values chosen it practically is.) The optimal amount the milkman should stock is then about 91 units, in which case his expected net gain is 39.1.",
